{% extends "layouts/doc-layout" %}

{% block title %}Escape Filter - Wisp Template Documentation{% end %}

{% block body %}
<h1>Escape Filter</h1>

<p>HTML-escapes a string, converting special characters to their entity equivalents. Use this filter when you need to explicitly escape content — for example, inside an HTML attribute value.</p>

<h2>Syntax</h2>
<pre><code>{% raw %}
{% .value | escape %}
{% endraw %}</code></pre>

<h2>Examples</h2>
<pre><code>{% raw %}
{% "<script>alert('xss')</script>" | escape %}
{% endraw %}</code></pre>
<p><strong>Output:</strong> &amp;lt;script&amp;gt;alert(&#39;xss&#39;)&amp;lt;/script&amp;gt;</p>
<p>The characters <code>&lt;</code>, <code>&gt;</code>, <code>&amp;</code>, <code>"</code>, and <code>'</code> are all converted to HTML entities.</p>

<pre><code>{% raw %}
{% .trusted_html | raw %}
{% .user_input | escape %}
{% endraw %}</code></pre>
<p>Contrast <code>raw</code> with <code>escape</code>: <code>raw</code> marks content as safe so the auto-escaper skips it, while <code>escape</code> <em>forces</em> escaping even on values that would otherwise be treated as safe.</p>

<h2>Notes</h2>
<ul>
  <li>HTML auto-escaping is on by default in Wisp, so most variables are already escaped at render time. The <code>escape</code> filter is useful when you need to explicitly escape a <code>SafeString</code> or when embedding a value inside an HTML attribute.</li>
  <li>To avoid double-escaping content that may already contain entities, use <a href="/docs/filters/escape_once">escape_once</a> instead.</li>
  <li>Never use <code>raw</code> on user-provided content — it bypasses all escaping and creates an XSS risk.</li>
</ul>

<h2>See Also</h2>
<ul>
  <li><a href="/docs/filters/escape_once">escape_once</a></li>
  <li><a href="/docs/filters/raw">raw</a></li>
</ul>
{% end %}
